24/ Sales is also about account management and retention. Most of my sponsors stay long-term, to help this: a. We speak regularly b. I use their product c. I stay up to speed on their innovations d. I meet with them when I can e. I give them feedback from listeners <!--1192361468186025984-->

23/ You will have to become comfortable with selling, therefore: a. Asking people to sponsor b. Following up on enquiries c. Asking again  With rates, my suggestion is to start low, sell out the ads and then raise your rates. Even offer an exclusive for a period of time. <!--1192361465245831168-->

22/ When selling sponsorships you are selling a story, why should they sponsor your show, for me: a. The reach of the audience b. The guests I get c. I record each ad fresh d. The ads work  It is that simple.  I get a lot of enquiries now and I have a rate card which I send out. <!--1192361463647784960-->

21/ So sponsors... My first step was when I started hitting 5k downloads per show, I offered some free ads out to condition the audience and potential sponsors.  Most of my sponsorships have come from me asking people, literally saying "hey will you sponsor my show". <!--1192361458673344514-->

20/ Okay, if you now have a show out there, you are in the grove, downloads are growing then this is where patience and consistency come in.  So many people give up because growth is slow or because they lack discipline. <!--1192361456039350273-->

19/ Step 7 - Additional things... a. Create a MailChimp account and connect to your website, collect emails and notify about new shows b. Register with Google Analytics and regularly look at your data c. Keep good spreadsheets tracking shows, guests, stats and ideas <!--1192361454747426822-->

19/ Really with marketing you are looking to build a profile around yourself as the host and your show. This requires a real grind, trying things, joining conversations etc...  You will make a bunch of mistakes here but don't worry. <!--1192361451106779136-->

18/ Step 6 - Marketing... So this is the long game, but I'll keep it as simple as possible a. Build a website with good content for SEO b. Build a profile on Facebook, Twitter, Instagram and LinkedIn c. Ask your listeners to help d. Ask guests to share shows <!--1192361448321830912-->

17/ Step 5 - Distribution... My view is to publish everywhere. If you use Libsyn for hosting then you can publish to most platforms direct (Apple, most Android apps).  Outside of Libsyn I: - Manually publish to SoundCloud - Auto publish to YouTube using http://Repurpose.io <!--1192361446941872133-->

16/ I think branding and design are really important but not essential. There are so many good tools out there to help you with this. I wrote a thread on it before: https://twitter.com/PeterMcCormack/status/1187496075923546113 <!--1192361442848182272-->

15/ Step 4 - Branding... Though you can do this earlier if you want. The choice is a topic-specific name v generic: a. Topic-specific like What Bitcoin Did is good for SEO and findability but restricts you to that category b. Generic is more flexible <!--1192361440621006849-->

14/ Step 3 - If you want an intro and outro, you can use Fiverr. I bought the one for WBD for $150.  Also, consider structure: a. WBD is Intro Music > Spoken Intro > Interview > Ad Break > Spoken Outro b. Defiance is Intro Music > Spoken Intro > Interview > Spoken Outro <!--1192361438532255744-->

13/ Step 2 - Master show... while I have an engineer now, I used to engineer my own shows. I would: a. Edit audio in Audacity b. Arrange show in Garage Band  Both are easy to understand but require time in the help files and YouTube guides.  Focus on cleaning the sound quality. <!--1192361436703600640-->

12/ Step 1 - Equipment... so for me, I invested in the best equipment from the start but you can literally start with an iPhone or a cheap microphone and record remotely on Zencastr.  Just work to your budget, my equipment: - Shure SM7B mics - Zoom H6 Desk - Wires + mic stands <!--1192361434283421696-->

11/ Long-term, for the interview style you need to consider online v in-person.  The latter is more demanding but I prefer it because: - Interviews are a higher quality - You build better relationships - You network more - You get interviews you wouldn't normally get <!--1192361432941236224-->

10/ After recording the show, if you think you want to make a podcast then great, time to prep.  The most important things early on are: a. Patience (can take a year for results) b. Consistency  Ignore money for now. <!--1192361429002866689-->

9/ I would then go and record a show, yep just go and make a recording. This is where you will learn most about yourself and the show you are making.  Don't worry if it is shit, just do it. Don't worry about how you sound listening back, everyone hates their own voice. <!--1192361425139838977-->
8/ What is your format? a. Interviews b. You talking to the microphone c. Produced series  All work and all are valid, just pick what you are comfortable with. <!--1192361421289508864-->

7/ Do you know what you want it to be about? Don't worry if there is competition, just do better than them.  If you are not sure then start with an audience need, why? a. You will be creating content people want to listen to b. You will have people sponsors want to reach <!--1192361418139537408-->

6/ So if you are prepared to put in the hard graft, are patient then you can make it work.  Don't worry about doubts or people saying "not another podcast", nobody podcasting says this.   First thing, go and follow the whole Pat Flynn course: https://www.smartpassiveincome.com/tutorials/start-podcast-pats-complete-step-step-podcasting-tutorial/ <!--1192361414859657216-->

5/ I didn't start selling ads until I hit 5k downloads, 12 months after launching the show.  So the truth is, and most podcasters will tell you the same, it is a lot of hard work, but if you can make it work it is a good life. <!--1192361413437804545-->

4/ 8 shows per month would bring in around $800 per month which will cover your costs and leave a little over.  If you sell 3 ads at $90, $270 * 8 = $2,160. Slightly better but you have to hit the 2.5k downloads + sell the ads. <!--1192361409226653696-->

3/ CPM ad rates vary, but: - Niche industry $30-$100 (eg Bitcoin) - Broad industry $15-$50 - Ad networks will tend to offer you $17-$30  Based on 2,500 downloads you have 2.5 * $30 (conservative) = $90 per advert. Though you could probably sell an exclusive at $100 per show. <!--1192361407263727616-->

2/ So you want to start a podcast...  I'll assume you want to make money from it, so let's start with that. Ad rates are calculated on something called the CPM, cost per mille (per thousand downloads).  My suggestion is to forget sponsors until you reach 2,500 downloads per show. <!--1192361404625555456-->

11/ If you want to get fancy and optimise your site for SEO then the Google guide is a great start.   https://support.google.com/webmasters/answer/7451184?hl=en   You want to integrate Google Webmaster Tools from the outset:  https://www.google.com/webmasters/#?modal_active=none   Use Moz for advanced stuff. https://moz.com <!--1187496108047720449-->

9/ For social banners, posts and website assets you again don‚Äôt have to be a designer.   There is a tool called Canva which will help you create any of these.   http://canva.com <!--1187496101861101573-->

8/ Social media marketing is likely to be very important. I‚Äôd suggest setting up which of the following are relevant to you: - Twitter - Facebook - LinkedIn - Instagram - YouTube - Medium - Pinterest  A great tool for automating your posting is Buffer. http://buffer.com <!--1187496094294523906-->

7/ I‚Äôd suggest spending plenty of time on your website, playing around with layouts and finding sites you like the look of.  A really great site for inspiration is dribbble. Look for button styles, don‚Äôt spacing etc...   http://dribbble.com <!--1187496093002670084-->

6/ Next up is your website. Many people love Wordpress because you can customise so much of it. Personally I think it is a UX nightmare. 5/ Next up you need a logo. This doesn‚Äôt have to cost much, you can contract someone on Fiverr but I think Looka is the shizzle.  They have different packages available which will create designs and social media icons. Remember to use your colours. https://looka.com/ <!--1187496089198514177-->

4/ Luckily you don‚Äôt need to be a designer these days to have a rad looking brand. The starting point is your colour scheme.  You don‚Äôt want shitty unmatching colours so use Coolors to@find a palette that works for you and religiously keep to it. https://coolors.co <!--1187496087877275648-->

3/ Next up is you need a name, if you want to crush Google then ideally you want the subject in the title + .com.  I got this right with WBD but with Defiance the name came first.   GoDaddy has a good search tool with alternative suggestions. https://godaddy.com <!--1187496086212169729-->

Edit 2: If you are not cut out for trading (like me), I wrote a thread on tools which can help you create your own business or a side gig. https://t.co/svz7sQS9Yy <!--1073201828366569472-->

<Conclusion>  There are hundreds of tools I haven't mentioned, these are just my personal favs and the ones I go back to again and again.  It is pretty easy to start a business these days, you can go from idea to a fully designed website in a day.  Good luck! <!--1073137643809095681-->

13/ If you want to build an online store then there is an option within Squarespace. If you want a dedicated option, then Shopify is pretty amazing. https://www.shopify.co.uk/ <!--1073137640923385858-->

12/ If you want to outsource something, for example I sometimes need help with SEO, specific graphics or audio, Fiverr is a great website. You can outsource jobs all over the world for a very low cost. https://fiverr.com <!--1073137636989198341-->
11/ For general admin I still like Google Drive for spreadsheets, documents etc... https://www.google.com/drive/ <!--1073137632715137025-->

10/ If you want to keep lists and notes, I recommend a little App called Bear (don't skip the tutorial). It is a great way of keeping notes and ideas together. https://bear.app/ <!--1073137630919966720-->

9/ If you want to get adventurous with your content and try and drive more traffic to your website, Moz is a great resource for optimising your site and finding things to write about. https://moz.com/ <!--1073137629636558853-->

8/ It is good to keep an eye on the performance of your website, what works and what doesn't. I would recommend using Google Analytics for this. When you register you will get a short code which you can put into your Squarespace site to track.  https://analytics.google.com/analytics/web/ <!--1073137627182837760-->

7/ If you want to create beautiful graphics for your websites, emails and social posts but you don't know how to design, then I would recommend Canva. Pretty much entirely free and all the hard work is done for you.  http://canva.com <!--1073137625765216256-->

6/ Social media is also going to be important to you. I would recommend as a minimum a Facebook page and a Twitter account though you may want Instagram too. You can create and schedule posts from Buffer for most social profiles. https://buffer.com <!--1073137624393629697-->

5/ Email marketing is one of your most important tools, make sure you have prominent email capture on your website. In terms of creating and sending emails, both Campaign Monitor and MailChimp are great, I favour the latter. https://mailchimp.com/ <!--1073137623198261249-->

4/ You probably want a website too. While many use Wordpress, I favour Squarespace. The interface is slick and their templates focus on design and are all mobile friendly by default. http://squarespace.com <!--1073137621998686208-->

3/ Assuming you have an idea and a name, you now need a logo. With Logojoy you can create a logo in about 5 minutes, pretty cheap too. You simply enter the name and play around with fonts and colours. https://logojoy.com/ <!--1073137620476137473-->

2/ Before you create a logo you need brand colours. Matching good colours are important and usually the work of a designer. With Coolors you can generate colour schemes. https://coolors.co/ <!--1073137619314372610-->

1/ First thing you need is a name. An important part to think about is SEO which is search engine optimisation. It is very helpful to have a keyword for your business in the name, for example, I have Bitcoin in mine.  https://namelix.com  is great for ideas <!--1073137618030870528-->

If you want to start a side gig, there are so many tools to help you get started. Here are a bunch of my favs.  Feel free to add to or critique.   With the tools listed in this <thread>, I reckon you can start an online business for less than $100 a month.  Cont... <!--1073137616038621184-->
